"Post E., Pedersen C., Wilmers C.C., Forchhammer M.C.","Warming, plant phenology and the spatial dimension of trophic mismatch for large herbivores",2008,"Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences","275","1646",,"2005","2013",,,10.1098/rspb.2008.0463,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-47249118728&partnerID=40&md5=5f84a0f55dde09ff1cd1181473d5167d","Department of Biology, Penn State University, 208 Mueller Lab., University Park, PA 16802, United States; Section for Climate Effects and System Modeling, Department of Arctic Environment, University of Aarhus, Frederiksborgvej 399, 4000 Roskilde, Denmark; Department of Environmental Studies, University of California-Santa Cruz, Santa Cruz, CA 95064, United States","Post, E., Department of Biology, Penn State University, 208 Mueller Lab., University Park, PA 16802, United States, Section for Climate Effects and System Modeling, Department of Arctic Environment, University of Aarhus, Frederiksborgvej 399, 4000 Roskilde, Denmark; Pedersen, C., Department of Biology, Penn State University, 208 Mueller Lab., University Park, PA 16802, United States; Wilmers, C.C., Department of Environmental Studies, University of California-Santa Cruz, Santa Cruz, CA 95064, United States; Forchhammer, M.C., Section for Climate Effects and System Modeling, Department of Arctic Environment, University of Aarhus, Frederiksborgvej 399, 4000 Roskilde, Denmark","Temporal advancement of resource availability by warming in seasonal environments can reduce reproductive success of vertebrates if their own reproductive phenology does not also advance with warming. Indirect evidence from large-scale analyses suggests, however, that migratory vertebrates might compensate for this by tracking phenological variation across landscapes. Results from our two-year warming experiment combined with seven years of observations of plant phenology and offspring production by caribou (Rangifer tarandus) in Greenland, however, contradict evidence from large-scale analyses. At spatial scales relevant to the foraging horizon of individual herbivores, spatial variability in plant phenology was reduced-not increased-by both experimental and observed warming. Concurrently, offspring production by female caribou declined with reductions in spatial variability in plant phenology. By highlighting the spatial dimension of trophic mismatch, these results reveal heretofore unexpected adverse consequences of climatic warming for herbivore population ecology. © 2008 The Royal Society.","Caribou; Climate change; Global warming; Life history; Plant phenology; Population dynamics","biological oceanography; deer; experimental study; foraging behavior; global warming; herbivore; life history; migratory species; phenology; population dynamics; population ecology; reproductive productivity; reproductive success; resource availability; spatial analysis; spatial variation; warming; article; breeding; climate change; foraging; greenhouse effect; Greenland; herbivore; life history; nonhuman; phenology; population dynamics; priority journal; progeny; reindeer; reproductive success; topography; Animals; Animals, Newborn; Ecosystem; Female; Greenhouse Effect; Multivariate Analysis; Plants; Population Dynamics; Regression Analysis; Reindeer; Arctic; Greenland; Rangifer tarandus; Vertebrata",,,,,,"Albon, S.D., Langvatn, R., Plant phenology and the benefits of migration in a temperate ungulate (1992) Oikos, 65, pp. 502-513. , doi:10.2307/3545568; Both, C., Visser, M.E., The effect of climate change on the correlation between avian life-history traits (2005) Glob. Change Biol, 11, pp. 1606-1613. , doi:10.1111/j.1365-2486.2005.01038.x; Both, C., Large-scale geographical variation confirms that climate change causes birds to lay earlier (2004) Proc. R. Soc. B, 271, pp. 1657-1662. , doi:10.1098/rspb.2004.2770; Bryant, J.P., Kuropat, P.J., Selection of winter forage by sub-arctic browsing vertebrates - the role of plant chemistry (1